5 Proteins as “hard” inclusion
We now argue that integral proteins of conical shape should be fundamentally considered as hard inclusions. First, it is very likely that the membrane elasticity is too weak to alter the conical shape of the protein, because of the strong dipolar interactions within the transmembrane protein domain (e.g., bundles of α-helices). Beside, a significant change in the protein shape would most probably alter its function. We can, therefore, assume that the protein behaves as a rigid conical body and that the weakness
of the curvature potential embodied in the parameter Γm arises fromthe tilt degree of freedomof the lipids. Let us consider a conical protein having a circular section of radius R in the membrane plane and an aperture angle 2θ. An estimate of Γm can be obtained by calculating the energy stored in the lipid tilt when one assumes that the membrane midplane remains perfectly flat. The latter is W ≈ Bθ2 × 2πR × ξ, where B is the elastic constant as
